## 8. Security System

- Security concept includes motion detection, camera events, smart-lock state, night security mode, away mode, and notification escalation.
- This document does not specify a certified alarm system, police/fire monitoring service, or guaranteed intrusion detection.
- Final security design should address tamper resistance, battery backup, entry/exit delays, sirens, manual panic options, nuisance alarms, privacy, and local licensing.

## 9. CCTV Concept

- PoE cameras are assumed at entry, driveway, terrace, and service approach locations.
- Prefer local recording with controlled remote viewing, clear retention limits, secure credentials, and camera VLAN isolation.
- Camera coverage must respect privacy, local law, signage requirements, neighboring properties, and areas where recording is restricted.

## 10. Access Control

- Smart locks are planning assumptions for convenience and status monitoring only.
- Every smart lock must retain manual/keyed override, emergency access, egress safety, battery replacement access, and owner-controlled credential management.
- Access-control logs and guest credentials must be protected as sensitive data.

## 11. Water Leak Protection

- Leak sensors are assumed in kitchen, bathrooms, laundry/storage, and technical room.
- Optional water shutoff automation must be professionally reviewed and must preserve manual bypass and access.
- Leak sensors do not replace waterproofing, floor drains, pipe insulation, maintenance, or winterization procedures.

## 12. Fire/CO Detection

- Smoke/CO sensors are life-safety systems and must be selected, powered, located, installed, and maintained according to applicable local requirements.
- Smart-home integration may mirror alerts but must not be the primary approved detection system.
- Fireplace, technical room, bedrooms, sleeping circulation, and any fuel-burning equipment require professional review.

## 13. Solar and Battery Monitoring

- Solar monitoring is a planning assumption for PV production, battery state, generator alerts, and outage visibility.
- Monitoring data should be treated as informational unless reviewed by licensed electrical professionals.
- Inverter, battery, generator, and transfer-system control must not be modified through unreviewed automations.

## 14. Remote Access

- Prefer VPN, secure tunnel, or managed remote access with MFA over exposed ports.
- Disable default accounts, avoid password reuse, rotate credentials, and document recovery access.
- Remote unlock, shutoff, heating, generator, and security actions must include confirmation and audit logging.

## 15. Backup and Restore

- Back up {{ smart_home.platform }} configuration, dashboards, automations, device registry, MQTT settings, and network/firewall configuration.
- Store backups encrypted, versioned, and separate from the controller.
- Test restore procedures after major changes and before relying on the system during winter vacancy.

## 16. Cybersecurity Checklist

- Change all default passwords and use unique credentials.
- Enable MFA for admin and remote-access accounts.
- Segment IoT, camera, guest, and admin networks.
- Keep controller, integrations, firmware, router/firewall, cameras, and apps updated.
- Disable unused services, UPnP, exposed ports, and weak protocols.
- Protect secrets, API keys, backup files, and camera streams.
- Review logs for failed login attempts, unusual traffic, device dropouts, and automation failures.

## 17. Maintenance Checklist

- Check battery devices and critical sensors on a scheduled basis.
- Confirm UPS runtime, battery health, and graceful shutdown behavior.
- Review camera lenses, mounts, storage capacity, retention policy, and firmware.
- Test leak alerts, smoke/CO alert mirroring, motion automations, away mode, night mode, and remote access.
- Review backups and restore procedure after platform upgrades.
- Keep a plain-language owner handover sheet for manual overrides, emergency access, and winter operating mode.

## QA Notes

- Smart-home convenience must not be confused with approved life-safety, security, or electrical systems.
- Cybersecurity and privacy warnings must remain visible in generated documents.
- All device locations, camera views, access-control behavior, and alarm workflows require owner and professional review.
